{
  "text": "Results showed that the Superior Incivility \u03eb Family Support interaction term significantly predicted work-to-family conflict (\u2424 \u03ed 0.18, p \u03fd .01; see Table  3 ), whereas the Coworker Incivility \u03eb Family Support interaction term significantly predicted perceived fairness (\u2424 \u03ed \u03ea0.12, p \u03fd .05) and depression (\u2424 \u03ed 0.24, p \u03fd .01; see Table 4 ). Using [CITATION_1] approach, we plotted the interactions using 1 standard deviation above and 1 standard deviation below the mean to represent high and low levels of the predictors, respectively. As shown in Figure 1 , the relationships between superior incivility and work-to-family conflict, between coworker incivility and perceived fairness, as well as between coworker incivility and depression were stronger when family support was high. Thus, Hypothesis 3a was rejected and Hypothesis 3b was supported.",
